03, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): nickname for someone with a blustery temperament, from Middle English, Old French <i>tempest(e)</i> ‘storm’ (from Latin <i>tempestas</i> ‘weather, season’, a derivative of <i>tempus</i> ‘time’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tempesta","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Raffaele, Agostino, Angelo, Carmelo, Cesare, Cesidio, Dante, Elio, Ezio, Gino.","Italian: nickname for someone with a stormy temperament, from <i>tempesta</i> ‘storm, tempest’ (see   Tempest  )."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Tempest was born about 1408, in Yorkshire, England, her father, William Tempest Knt., was 37 and her mother, Alianore Washington, was 26. She married Richard Norton Esq. on 29 January 1426. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1452, in Norton Conyers, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"about 1408–by 1452":"umbes 1408–1452","1408–1452":"1408–1452","1410–1462":"1410–1462","1417–1443":"1417–1443","1388–1438":"1388–1438","1427–1489":"1427–1489","1373–1441":"1373–1441","1384–1451":"1384–1451","22 September 1438":"22. september 1438","1451":"1451","1462":"1462","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","about 1408":"umbes 1408","8 June 1441":"8. juuni 1441","1489":"1489","1388":"1388","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","July 1427":"juuli 1427","2 January 1451":"2. jaanuar 1451"